SIMPLE: auspice
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Auspice
<hw>Aus"pice</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Auspices</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>auspicium</ets>,
fr. <ets>auspex</ets>: cf. F. <ets>auspice</ets>. See
<er>Auspicate</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A divining or
taking of omens by observing birds; an omen as to an undertaking, drawn
from birds; an augury; an omen or sign in general; an indication as to
the future.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Protection; patronage and care; guidance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which by his <qex>auspice</qex> they will nobler make.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In this sense the word is generally plural,
<xex>auspices</xex>; as, under the <xex>auspices</xex> of the
king.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Auspicial</ent>⟦br⟧
